# History & Timeline (2010–2020)

## Background (Pre-2010 Context)

Faysal Bank Limited traces its roots to 1987, when it began as a branch operation of Faysal Islamic Bank of Bahrain. In 1995, its Pakistani operations were incorporated as Al-Faysal Investment Bank and listed on the Karachi Stock Exchange. In 2002, this investment bank merged with the conventional banking arm, forming the Faysal Bank known today. Naved A. Khan took over as head of the bank in 2008, setting the stage for the decade of change that followed.

## Year-by-Year Milestones

### 2010 — The RBS Pakistan Acquisition
Under Naved Khan's leadership, Faysal Bank acquired the Pakistan operations of RBS (Royal Bank of Scotland) for approximately £34 million. This was a landmark deal because RBS Pakistan had itself previously absorbed the Pakistan operations of ABN AMRO, which in turn had earlier acquired Prime Commercial Bank (69 branches across 24 cities) in 2007. Through this chain of acquisitions, Faysal Bank significantly expanded its branch footprint and customer base overnight.

### 2011–2013 — Integration Phase
Leadership transitioned to Nauman Ansari, who focused on:
- Integrating the newly acquired RBS branch network into Faysal Bank's existing systems and culture
- Streamlining operations and reducing an overgrown workforce resulting from the merger
- Repositioning the bank for renewed growth after a period of consolidation

### 2014 — The Islamic Banking Announcement
Faysal Bank announced its intention to convert into a full-fledged Islamic bank over a three-to-five-year horizon. This was a strategic response to the faster deposit growth being observed in Pakistan's Islamic banking sector compared to conventional banking, and it marked the beginning of a long-term transformation that would eventually reshape every department of the bank.

### 2015–2018 — Gradual Islamic Conversion & Branch Expansion
- Continued conversion of conventional branches into Islamic (Shariah-compliant) branches
- Expansion of the branch network, including reports of large-scale branch rollouts (e.g., coverage of a 200-new-branch expansion push reported around 2019)
- Development of Shariah-compliant retail products under what would later be branded as "Faysal Islami"

### 2019 — Continued Network Growth
Faysal Bank continued its aggressive branch expansion strategy, investing heavily in growing its retail footprint across Pakistan as part of its broader Islamic banking transition strategy.

### 2020 — Regulatory Milestone & Continued Transition
In July 2020, the State Bank of Pakistan (SBP) issued a fine of approximately Rs. 96.1 million against the bank for compliance-related violations concerning Customer Due Diligence (CDD), foreign exchange handling, Know-Your-Customer (KYC) protocols, and asset quality in operations. This event is a notable regulatory milestone within the decade and reflects the compliance challenges large banks face during periods of rapid transformation.

## Beyond 2020 (For Context)

While outside this project's core scope, it's worth noting that Faysal Bank formally completed its transition into a fully Islamic bank in 2023 — the culmination of the process that began with the 2014 announcement documented above.

## Summary Table

| Year | Milestone |
|---|---|
| 2010 | Acquisition of RBS Pakistan (~£34 million) |
| 2011–2013 | Post-acquisition integration under Nauman Ansari |
| 2014 | Announcement of full conversion to Islamic banking |
| 2015–2018 | Gradual branch conversion to Islamic banking model |
| 2019 | Major branch network expansion |
| 2020 | SBP regulatory fine (~Rs. 96.1 million) for compliance violations |

